Breastfeeding can be hard, and it is a personal journey for each breastfeeding individual. Often there are no hard and fast rules to follow as what works for one individual may not for another. In this video, Dr. @talibogler chats with lactation consultant Sofya Brainin about breast milk supply and beyond.
⠀
@1:34 “What are some risk factors for having less or delayed milk supply?”
@3:36 “What are the signs a parent should look for to tell whether the baby is feeding enough in the first few days of life?”
@6:04 “What are the methods to stimulate breast milk supply immediately after the delivery of the baby (first 48 hours)?”
@8:14 “When might someone require extra breast simulation to promote their milk supply?”
@9:50 “What do you recommend for someone whose milk supply hasn’t come in yet in the first 2 or even 3 days after delivery? Will this affect the baby’s health?”
@13:40 “Why is hydration important for breast milk supply?”
@17:19 “Does lack of rest affect breast milk supply?”
@21:23 “What should a parent do when they feel like their milk supply is not meeting their baby’s demand?
@24:40 “Does taking herbal supplements help to promote breast milk supply?”
@26:56 “How does stress and wellness impact breast milk supply?”
31:15 Sofya shares her “pyramid philosophy to feeding.”
@34:12 How to get breastfeeding support virtually.
⠀
Sofya is an International Board Certified Lactation Consultant. She works at St. Michael’s Hospital helping new parents establish and continue a healthy breastfeeding relationship.
